<h1>divisibility</h1>

<p>
This study of integers begins with the notion of <em>divsibility</em>: whether
the division of two integers results in an integer.  Since division does not
always yield a result at all, let alone an integer result, we frame this
question in terms of multiplication.
</p>

<div class="definition">
  <p>
    A nonzero integer <code>b</code> <strong>divides</strong> an integer
    <code>a</code> if there exists some integer <code>n</code> such that
    <code>a == b * n</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The notation for this is <code>b | a</code>, which reads "<code>b</code>
    divides <code>a</code>".  The following statements are equivalent ways of
    describing that <code>b | a</code>.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <% divisibility_statements("b", "a", divisible: true).each do |statement| %>
      <li><%= statement %></li>
    <% end %>
  </ul>
</div>

<p>
  Here are a couple of examples:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <code>15 | 45</code> since <code>45 == 15 * 3</code>.  In other words,
    <ul>
      <% divisibility_statements(15, 45).each do |statement| %>
        <li><%= statement %></li>
      <% end %>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <code>10 âˆ¤ 45</code> since <code>45 != 10 * n</code> for any <code>n</code>.
    In fact, <code>45</code> is strictly between <code>10 * 4</code> and <code>10 * 5</code>.
    In other words,
    <ul>
      <% divisibility_statements(15, 45).each do |statement| %>
